Kethari water-memory of the eastern aquifer predates the Water Court's institutional formation — the Kethari knew the oasis springs before the Keepers surveyed them.
The Water Court's four-cistern system formalized what Kethari water-readers had known for generations: the springs are a confluence of distinct flows with different seasonal behaviors.
Kethari assessment: the underlying aquifer structure is sound despite institutional collapse — the water remains where it always was.
The Deepwell Confluence name in pre-dynastic clay seals matches Kethari oral memory of the site, confirming hydraulic understanding predated Keeper survey documentation.
Kethari water-memory includes the aquifer's response to the Ninth Meridian Rite: the springs did not fail, but their seasonal timing shifted in ways current administrators still have not fully accounted for.
Accurate assessment of the oasis water-cycle requires both Deltari flow records and Kethari long-memory — neither alone is sufficient.
